INPUT IN PYTHON

🔹 What is input()?
   input() is a built-in Python function used to take input from the user.

⚠️ Important Rule
👉 input() always returns data as a string (str), even if you type a number.

🔹 Basic Syntax
        variable = input("message")

Example:
        name = input("Enter your name: ")

🔹 Why Type Conversion is Needed
   Since input() gives string data, we must convert it for calculations.

Example Problem
code:   age = input("Enter age: ")

⚠️ Here, age is a string, not a number.

To calculate:
code:   age = int(input("Enter age: "))

🔹 Common Type Conversions with Input
         ________________ _____________________
        | Data Needed	 |     Syntax          |
        |________________|_____________________|
        |   Integer	     |   int(input())      |
        |   Float	     |   float(input())    |
        |   String	     |   input()           |
        |________________|_____________________|

🔹 Input in Data Analytics
Used for:
    Taking dataset size
    User-defined thresholds
    KPI values
    Parameters for analysis
code:  total_sales = float(input("Enter total sales: "))        


🔹 Multiple Inputs

👶NOOB WAY
code: a = int(input("Enter first value: "))
      b = int(input("Enter second value: "))

🔰PRO WAY
🔹 Input from Same Line (Advanced)
code: a, b = map(int, input("Enter two values: ").split())

🔹 Common Mistakes
   ❌ Using commas in numbers
   ❌ Forgetting type conversion
   ❌ Mixing strings and numbers